# WHAT IT IS
#   Aether is "a compiled actor-based programming language
#   with type inference, designed for concurrent systems."
#   It compiles to readable C and exposes seamless C
#   interoperability, sitting closer to functional than OO on
#   the paradigm spectrum (no classes, no inheritance, no
#   method dispatch — structs are plain data, behaviour is
#   free functions; the only OO machinery is the actor:
#   stateful, encapsulated behind a message boundary).
#
#   Headline features:
#     • Actor-based concurrency with automatic multi-core
#       scheduling (locality-aware partitioned scheduler with
#       work-stealing fallback, lock-free SPSC same-core
#       queues, cross-core lock-free mailboxes)
#     • Type inference with optional annotations
#     • Compiles to readable C (portability + C library
#       interop)
#     • Three-layer capability model for sandboxing untrusted
#       code:  `--emit=lib` gates stdlib at compile time,
#       `hide`/`seal except` gates scopes, LD_PRELOAD gates
#       libc
#     • Go-style result types: `a, err = func()` with `_`
#       discard
#     • Package management: `ae add host/user/repo[@version]`
#       (GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, any git host)
#     • PATH-style module search via
#       `--lib ./lib:./vendor/stdlib` /
#       `AETHER_LIB_DIR=...` (resolution chain shown by
#       `ae lib-path`)
#     • Production-grade HTTP server in stdlib — TLS,
#       HTTP/1.1 keep-alive, HTTP/2 (h2 + h2c via libnghttp2
#       with ALPN + GOAWAY + pthread pool), WebSocket
#       (RFC 6455), Server-Sent Events, zero-copy
#       `sendfile(2)` static-file serving, composable
#       middleware (CORS, basic/bearer/session-cookie auth,
#       rate limiting, real-IP, vhost, gzip, static files,
#       rewrite, error pages), `/healthz` + `/readyz`,
#       structured access logs, Prometheus metrics
#     • nginx-class reverse proxy in stdlib (`std.http.proxy`
#       with five load-balancing algorithms, active health
#       checks, LRU response cache, circuit breaker, retry
#       with `proxy_next_upstream` semantics, W3C
#       Trace-Context, Prometheus metrics)
#     • `--emit=lib` symbol-catalog reflection
#       (`AetherLibMeta` exported as `static const` in
#       `.rodata` — walks straight from Python ctypes /
#       Java Panama / Ruby Fiddle / Go cgo / hand-rolled
#       `dlsym`); `ae lib-info <path>` is a turnkey reader
#     • `--emit=lib` resource caps (process memory ceiling
#       via `aether_set_memory_cap` + per-thread wall-clock
#       deadline via `aether_set_call_deadline`; codegen
#       emits zero-overhead tripwires at every loop head)
#     • Automatic string-ownership tracking (compiler-emitted
#       `_heap_<name>` companion flips on reassignment, no
#       explicit `defer string.free(s)`)
#     • Eiffel-style runtime contracts: `requires` /
#       `ensures` clauses lower to per-call panic checks;
#       `--no-contracts` build flag suppresses emission
#       entirely (zero per-call cost — the analog of C's
#       `-DNDEBUG`)
#     • `ae help <script>` — offline diagnostics for
#       closure-DSL config scripts (no network calls, no
#       file reads outside the script + imports; optional
#       `--llm` escalation when built with
#       `AETHER_ENABLE_LLM=1`)
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from tools/ae.c subcommand
#                       dispatch + per-`cmd_*` function help
#                       text; extracted via `gh api repos/
#                       aether-lang-org/aether/contents/
#                       tools/ae.c`)
#
#   ae <SUBCOMMAND> [args...]
#
#   Project lifecycle:
#     init <NAME>                    Create a new Aether
#                                    project under <NAME>/
#     run [<FILE.ae>]                Compile and run a program
#                                    (default: main entry from
#                                    aether.toml)
#     build [<FILE.ae>]              Compile to executable
#                                    (without running)
#     check [<FILE.ae>]              Type-check the program
#                                    only (no codegen, no
#                                    execute)
#     test [<FILE|DIR>]              Run tests (file, or
#                                    directory walk)
#     repl                           Start the interactive
#                                    REPL
#     fmt [<FILE>]                   Format source code  (not
#                                    yet implemented — placeholder)
#
#   Package management:
#     add <PACKAGE>                  Add a dependency  (e.g.
#                                    `ae add github.com/user/
#                                    repo` or
#                                    `ae add gitlab.com/user/
#                                    repo@v1.2.3`)
#     cache                          Manage the local package
